    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <date>October 13th 1863</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <placeName>San Francisco California</placeName>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I suppose<lb/> you are <sic>surprized</sic> I did not write to you
                for<lb/> so long. I have nothing of much interest to<lb/> you. Enclosed I send you
                some items, which<lb/> probably you may be disposed to notice in<lb/> your Journal.
                I have only stated facts<lb/> up to the present I have not yet received<lb/> the
                parcel you sent me it has been mislaid<lb/> but they have promised to look for it
                and<lb/> send it to me, and then I will acknowledge<lb/> it. Your Books I find hard
                to sell. One<lb/>
                <sic>sett</sic> I have sold. I will collect the money<lb/> and send it to you
                shortly as also some from<lb/> myself. I think I could sell 2 <sic>setts</sic>
                of<lb/> your <sic>portuguese</sic>
                <add>מחזורים</add> complete if<lb/> you have them the Octavo Edition send<lb/> me
                the lowest price, and let the freight be<lb/> small as the people grudge to pay
                the<lb/> same. I send you enclosed a prospectus<lb/> of my proposed little work
                which I intend<lb/> shortly to publish and then will send some<lb/> copies to you by
                opportunities which may often<lb/> be same expense..possibly you can dispose</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of some of them. My plan is to secure<lb/> sufficient subscribers to pay the
                expense<lb/> so that I have no outlay—altho' it is<lb/> attended with some trouble.
                I am much<lb/> pleased with your rejoinder to <persName>Mr De<lb/> Solla</persName>
                in the interment question. He must<lb/> be a great <add>עזות פנים</add>. I should
                feel greatly<lb/> obliged to you to send me his pamphlet<lb/> and the <persName>Revd
                    Mr Nathans</persName> reply on the<lb/> subject of the <add>עוזר</add> married
                by him<lb/> some time ago. You can send it through<lb/> the post and I will pay the
                cost</p>
            <p>Do you know that <persName>Mr Nathan</persName> is engaged<lb/> at <placeName>St
                    Thomas'</placeName> in the place of <persName>Mr<lb/> Myers</persName> late of
                    <placeName>London</placeName> who is now at<lb/>
                <placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName>, <hi rend="underline">entre vous</hi>. He
                is<lb/> a real charlatan. I know him from<lb/> childhood—what a pity that
                congregations<lb/> are not more particular in engaging them<lb/> as ministers! We
                hear nothing in this Region<lb/> of <persName>Wise</persName> and
                    <persName>Lilienthal</persName>—I suppose you<lb/> do. How goes the War? I hope
                you were<lb/> in health to perform your duties on the late<lb/> Holy days—let me
                hear from you soon<lb/> I am always pleased to read your letters<lb/> Trusting this
                will reach in health and<lb/> happiness    Believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">H. A. Henry</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
